No liberating novel for Tymoshenko by parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the paragraph on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted, as part of a novel of the criminal code.
The new arrangement, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected by the MPs in the second reading of the request for mitigation of penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for signing a allegedly detrimental gas purchase agreement with Russia.
The verdict is not yet final, and the appeal of the convicted will be heard in court in December.
Timoshenko himself described the verdict as a political revenge of the regime and even in the West the process raised suspicion of the court’s bias.
The petition, Paragraph 365, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted to be removed from the criminal code, was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been needed to pass it.
