The beginning of a new crisis
France and the rest of Europe in the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical thunderstorm broke across Europe.
Each country published its GDP data for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, with Germany and France declining.
The bond market is breaking all records.
Investors are now keeping an eye on not only Greece, but also Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical offices of the European zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and several other European countries released their preliminary forecasts on economic development in the third quarter.
As expected, Germany’s GDP grew by 0.5% and France’s by 0.4%.
Both countries simultaneously corrected their data for the second quarter, in which Germany recorded greater growth than originally expected (growth of 0.3% instead of the forecasted 0.1%), while France admitted a slight decline of 0.1% (original data spoke only of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year.
However, compared to the previous quarter, GDP stagnated and, according to the Chief Statistical Office, this confirmed the trend of slowing growth in economic performance.
The results are worse than analysts’ forecasts.
The most important events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year, but it stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to preliminary and seasonal data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
In the eurozone as a whole and in the EU, the economy grew by 0.2% between July and September compared to the previous quarter, which is in line with analyst expectations.
The Greek economy shrunk by 5.2% compared to the previous year.
The yield on their 10-year government bonds rose to 28.45%.
The yields of Italian and Spanish government bonds rose to their critical limits.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries are also beginning to feel problems.
