The menu of a fat addicted child: He doesn’t eat breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than one-third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have proven - obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyle.
This once again shows how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had potatoes for dinner on the eve of the awareness campaign under the motto "Adiposity is not a coincidence."
Sport is not one of the favourite activities in families with small thicknesses, but it also affects the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent said their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of the school year last year and involved almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the campaign "Adiposity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th classes have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are key factors that are responsible for the frightening increase in the number of children who are overweight or even obese.
"Only half of the children surveyed, for example, led to eating five times a day, in the mode breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper-dinner bread - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," one of the survey results says.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative little things, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are important for a child’s healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the families of students eat breakfast.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast for themselves.
The worst was the finding that one in ten families doesn’t have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the foundation of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test revealed, among other things, that in families with overweight children, unhealthy potatoes are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sport, only less than half of their parents do – namely, only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own meal plans based on their appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is especially the high popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main dish, pasta was over poultry.
The children almost didn’t like peanuts at all and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the educational lecture "Adiposity is not a coincidence", there was in many cases a marked shift in preferences toward the principles of healthy eating," is stated in the results of the project.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed chicken or fish as the main dish of the day much more often in the questionnaire and were willing to eat fewer snacks or sweet foods.
