Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Resignation
The initially careless ride becomes a routine ride to the early class by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant mistakes.
It was possible to fulfill the ambitions for the most part, but what use would it have if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before it came to the table, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already aged game series "Need for Speed" back into a new dimension, and in the playable demonstration examples he actually seemed to be not just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the matched passages go out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you’re used to NFS, in the end, it’s a lot different than you expected.
Sure – potentially they’re pretty decent arcade races, but overall the game is crushed by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So, in fact, they are no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a in principle incomprehensible laziness of game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
First introduced to the story, the main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the wheel with the task of being first in New York.
The basic idea includes a whole host of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race takes place on a different track and that each stage takes place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You have no moment of the impression that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
Nothing worldwide.
But driving through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deep snow landscape seem visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, unusual elements bring a little variation to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm, which severely restricts sight.
In the mountains, however, you have to be careful not to be spilled by a avalanche.
At the same time, the individual races are well arranged.
Just a few, but they are enough.
For a while, you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to pick up (classical race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
There is also the police who are trying to get involved in the whole matter.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It’s more about certain interactive animations where Jack runs away from somebody and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (specifically probably only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage of the thing, because so at least this element has no chance of becoming boring - it is in the context of the above mentioned among the elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model moves in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, although it does not tear down trees, on the other hand, one could not claim it would be bad.
Anyone looking for realistic simulations must look elsewhere.
But for an action-laden race, the local driving model will continue to be quite good, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems arise only after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not entirely OK.
From a game of this kind, it is hard to expect that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea of how the car behaves before hitting any object, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: in the close overhaul or passing by oncoming cars, in some places one "stripes" the other car only easily, in other, almost identical situation one comes into the slide and turns wild pirouettes.
Or the car is going to rot.
Thanks to the restart system, this does not matter, but it is always annoying.
The restarts are resolved in this way: if you have total damage or land far from the track, then you throw the game back to the last point of the track.
In each race, you only have five restarts.
Once you have exhausted them, everything starts from the beginning.
So the restarts are more like a tool in case something fails, but you should not rely on it.
Sometimes even restarting doesn’t help, as it helps nothing but to learn the critical section from the head.
Very unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, must be done in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
In other places, you will always encounter “civil” cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent passing by two opposing cars in front of a player, but before you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
Contractors have other advantages.
Thro the game there are a few places where you will always be overtaken at the same place by the same opponent and here again regardless of the time.
The most crazy thing is to finish the game on the long bridge, which happens in opposite direction.
The contractor must obviously get out of here.
And if he is already in front of one, then he naturally takes a sight, so that you initially drive your own car a few times in Klump.
Clearly – you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly loses you the pleasure of the game.
And that is a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining overall and sometimes so action-laden that you almost no longer know where one’s head is.
And in principle it doesn't matter what "blame" is about it - the concept of fifty unique routes, arranging the races in a way that can't get bored, or something quite different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car during the race.
You should not ignore the gas stations on the route, because it is here that you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have right now is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are good for urban areas, the strong American limousines for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game story goes also the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points to earn for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and the story.
To get to the higher driver level, various objects must be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also connected with the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your own results with those of other players and also provides additional collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible scratches is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (because of me), where you run on the rails in the dark (because of me).
On the Tacho numbers look between 150 and 200 km / h (in my opinion), but there suddenly comes from behind a subway and drives an uncompromising waste.
In our editorial office, we will probably argue for a long time whether this was a blackout by the game makers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
Even more annoying is the fact that in some exciting moments the image repeat rate becomes slower and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
This, however, especially affects accidents with a greater number of participants, where a continuous FPS is not useful anyway.
The sound is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to reach as many young audiences as possible, a soundtrack a lá "of everyone something" was created - but who buys such a game because of the music?
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? the feelings are rather mixed.
If the game wasn’t shrunk by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have argued with the brunt of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
The game seems somehow unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared to face these mistakes with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "Students of the Saten Revolution" with singing ensembles of the Charles University
The Festa Academica Festival now offers for the third time the celebration of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Samtenen Revolution and this together with a musical experience.
During the festival, twenty professional and university choirs will present themselves.
The focus of the festival is the two concerts that will take place on November 17.
“The University of Charles has a large share of the festival.”
"Among the participants is also represented the choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, and in the festival committee, among others, also the Rector Václav Hampl," said the head of the organizing team, Jakub Čaloun.
The absolute highlight of the festival is the public concert of vocational school choirs, which will take place on November 17 from 14:00 on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
On the program is the composition of the prominent Czech jazz artist Karel Růžička "Celebration Jazz Mass".
In the evening hours, in the galleries of the People's House in Vinohrady, the concert "Students of the Saten Revolution" (Studenty sametu) will take place, which will also feature university choirs, not excluded choirs of the University of Charles.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the World Student Day with dignity and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Seed Revolution, but also to present choir music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative collaboration of young people.
The main organizer is the Association of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes-Kepler Gymnasium.
The patronage of the entire event was assumed by Bohuslav Svoboda, mayor of the capital Prague, and Václav Hampl, rector of the University of Charles.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to festival concerts, the schedule also includes numerous music meetings, student happanings, matinees and other events.
Detailed information can be found on the festival’s website www.festaacademica.cz
