IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, the company IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was first adopted in 1924 as a trademark for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous card clocks for recording the beginning and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also served as chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competitive company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
This leader then even overshadowed the founders of IBM - based on Watson's ideas to this day, the company's invincible culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the manufacture and distribution of all types of machinery for trade - from sausage and cheese cutting machines to boxers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its revenue to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chair of the company for forty years before being replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA to direct flights into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that defined the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it bought the consultancy share of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high value added.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the "Smart Planet" concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and urban administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform, which is designed to help traders drive the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition technology.
