Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the then-CSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At the time, the travel agencies sold only trips to the socialist countries of the Eastern bloc, but only selected people were allowed to travel to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the Czechoslovak Republic wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered to travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter had not been long gone.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for leaving the West - was granted only to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
In fact, the Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dachas - a custom that continues to this day.
The 1989 Saten Revolution was followed by a travel revolution by the Czechs.
While until 1989 a vacation in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their overseas holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange obligation to neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which triggered a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna, Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough from their long trips to the West, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
Thus, Czech holidaymakers slept in tents in the park when traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money at the time for accommodation in a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of Czechs travelling abroad at the time was a suitcase packed with canned foods, beer and permanent sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists could finally freely buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living and, as a result, average wages increased, which marked another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, the travel agencies began to regularly prepare travel by charter flights, which thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantitative discounts, made air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-Saman" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight was made to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have been flying to distant sunny countries every year; this year, 12 exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
Every year, Czechs travel to exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%), and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 per capita for a single vacation, including the cost at the resort.
