21st House in Vienna
The Moving Flag
by Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with heights, depths and happy ends: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and went away.
It is now being reopened as an exhibition house.
If shrouded by modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition is a striking and famous example.
Schwanzer's pavilion was then awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so well known that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next World Exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a bowl-like side building in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was set up in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna Southern Railway Station after the World Exhibition, was rebuilt and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century was opened in it - the "20th House" was called.
However, the building was not suitable spatially and technically as a museum - no walls to hang art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used for so long until contemporary art in Vienna got a new home.
Since 2001, the building was empty and went down more and more.
Now architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum of contemporary art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens its first exhibition - a lucky case in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a Ph.D. art historian with a remarkable career, including in her youth as a ice art runner, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modernity, insisted on the reformation among politicians and heritage defenders, she raised public funds and private sponsorship funds and established the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookstore were to be built, and an office house was to be built for it.
Strict supervision, small staff
For the execution, Krischanitz was the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensibly rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him a "extremely important place" where he had watched the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and ease when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
There were far greater problems with the current reconstruction: the building was “an energy shuttle,” Krischanitz says.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, insulating glass reinforced by glass fiber was used and the glass roof was replaced with a special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel carriers have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements made room for the new use, a lowered light graft between the house and the street provides exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red brown rust-protective shade.
The cinema is exactly the same as it was before.
And all this under strict supervision of the Monument Authority and with a small mandate.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the Monument Protection Office," Krischanitz says, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and reconstructions, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
It was difficult with the pavilion, “which came from Brussels,” Krischanitz recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city story.”
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "wake up a proper consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because there has been an urban accident: around the Swiss garden the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofquartier", with office and residential buildings, is being created.
And another fortune may happen: the 21st house could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporäre Kunsthalle, and as you hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborhood site in the Swiss Garden.
