Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who posted their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who has confessed to committing a July shooting in Norway that killed 77 people, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time before his attack in front of his computer chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networks.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the page’s advertising tool to accurately determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million supporters of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking themselves to a new band or diet product, the adds invited users to a survey in which they were asked about their educational status, attitude toward violence, and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without having to leave their offices.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” says Bartlett.
Online supporters of right-wing extremist groups are mostly young, male and upset about immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factory, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends such as “likes”, text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom that has led to the number of scientific works with the name of this page in the title increasing by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beautiful thing about Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people you don’t normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you previously tried to question people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have allowed them access,” says Bartlett.
“At Facebook, it all goes away – you go straight to them.”
Others say the site provides a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their bullying on Facebook are significantly more inclined to problem drinking than students who remain silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that peer-to-peer students, such as housing consultants, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem unless you’ve recognized it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise."
Facebook also constantly wipes up the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has generated statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voting participation in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using data that only Facebook has access to – masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data mine available to others for research purposes.)
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not.In order to play scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to disclose their own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know anything about yet?
While researchers have strictly defined policies on how to collect their data offline, everything online is allowed.
"I don't think many users have thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles at all," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
“As for her, it was just about her and her friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and pen is still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research has to take care of the social – and a lot of social life is still taking place offline.”
