Stories about cheating in school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been instances where teachers predicted the exam answers to their students so that they could be good at their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies have shown that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
However, many of these lies are considered urgent lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or “discovering lies” is one that is important to learn for every person, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as charades in which the goal is to call “Have you!” the enthusiasm of a deception is a reputable field of knowledge based on scientific data gathered over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have carried out extensive research projects, in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the ancient myths about lies have been uncovered.
Lies look in the eyes.
They stumble, stumble, red and stumble not always.
However, it should not be concluded that these liars are difficult to uncover and uncover.
A trained liar detector can penetrate the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the subtle facial expressions, questioning and timing.
I have spent several years exploring the scientific findings of the extensive and ever-growing field of detection.And it is clear that the detachment of a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find judgment in our complex world, especially when hiring or interrogating people or negotiating or administering is part of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at evaluating other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people are more likely to lie than introverted people, that men are more likely to open up “self-oriented” lies than women whose lies are more “to-other” – usually they want to protect the feelings of others – that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly “fat lies”).
We also know that when a person is exposed as a perpetrator, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice quality of your subject.
You should better know when someone normally trips with the foot constantly so that they don’t wrongly blame him if he trips with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of striking verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that scream, not as evidence of a decay.
People who cheat may stiffen when they try to remember their story.Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way, or show a "relaxation after the adjustment conversation", that deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questionnaires often erroneously signal that a job interview is over just to keep looking for that relaxation after the job interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson’s glider is famous for using the past form when he claimed his killed wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Misleading individuals can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky” or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use “qualifying language” when answering a tricky question: “Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience.”
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, often causing the alarm bells to whistle.
There is no magic remedy to detach lies, but you can learn skills that make detachment possible.
Thanks to these skills, anyone is less likely to become a victim of fraud, both in personal and professional life.
