Climate change is slowing the economy
In the first year Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and black labour rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of change and sparked great hopes regarding economic growth, is in the government.
The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also tightened the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter This is mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which had a braking effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report on the effects of the frost, published by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78,03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21,07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has caused unemployment to continue to rise in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid rise in unemployment in the first quarter, as from January to March 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa were unemployed, equivalent to 4,53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74,000 unemployed in Sinaloa. This is 18 969 people more than in the first quarter.
Less liquidity
Economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), commented that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including losses of liquidity in the market due to fund cuts by legislation passed to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who illegally accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them, or use them for anything else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also an inherent demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased.This is due, on the one hand, to the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is difficult to find work there too.These people stay here and look for work here, which causes unemployment to rise,” he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is even more serious if you consider the high percentage of black labour, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 percent of the country’s employees who work without paying to the social security funds.
Unemployment and black work include low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institution) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexican Government Agency for Labour and Social Welfare).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos as of September, which is much less than the national average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 saw the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years. According to the Secretaría de Economía (governmental economic authority), the ADI was $630,597 from January to June, representing a decline of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Governmental Authority for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, primarily from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In the face of the economic crisis, in July, the state government applied to the National Congress for a loan of 3 000 000 000 Pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy.
Reactions
For representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of Mario López Valdés’s rule made the government’s inability obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (Mexican State Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry), stated that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of the various sectors, including the state government.
“Economic activity in Sinaloa has really been very poor this year. It has to be worked hard to recover the land lost this year and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. The efforts of all and especially the progress of the already well-defined government team have not been adequately coordinated,” he explained.
Slow economic development
Loredo López stated that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year complicated and slowed the country’s economic development.
“The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost.One of the main effects is a slowing economy that is not moving enough to generate an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services.
Re-defining the call
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana in Sinaloa, stated that the state must be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There is a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will better guide the government’s efforts.
"Overall, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas.The economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress with the government.
“There are areas in which you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively; what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is a lot of work ahead of it,” he said.
