Court Approves Transition to Digital Television in Mexico for 2015
The shift from analog to digital signals is one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree requiring the switch from analog to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 due to the lack of eight votes needed to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, believed that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the legislative decree detailing the switch to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate because it did not obtain the required qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide whether it was constitutional or non-constitutional.
The draft lawsuit, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed that the legislative decree be declared unconstitutional as regulations relating to radio and television are the responsibility of the Commission Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which would be contrary to the hierarchical principles and the provisions of the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Representatives submitted constitutional complaints against the legislative decree.After accepting the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero ceased to apply the legislative decree and ceased all activities to establish digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the appeal submitted by the Chamber of Deputies, without participating in the debate on the project, for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his speech, the Prime Minister expressed his disagreement with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the state government cannot regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration by means of general rules.
She also recalled that for constitutional reasons, the central government is responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, because it manages state affairs.
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in better use of the radio spectrum, increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, she said, was a postponement of the benefits of digitalization, which is a decision in the public interest, which has not only technical aspects, "because it includes economic, social, political and security technical aspects."
These matters, she emphasized, "requireed the action of the whole system, according to the principle of economic management by the state, they included a set of features that the constitution puts in the hands of the central state government."
She recalled that many countries around the world have already carried out the digital transformation, through the government, despite having highly specialized institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government would interfere with the competence of Congress by issuing the contested legislative decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be respected," she said.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán separately is considered
According to PREP data, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of counting the ballots separately is a reality at this year’s Michoacán elections, as according to the data released by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the Governor’s elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still not counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9 the Electoral Office adopted a series of regulations to harmonize local regulations with the federal reforms in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force at this election round.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional lawsuit filed by the local legislature and deemed the vote of the State Commissioner on the constitutional reforms “invalid and unlawful” as he has no right to “decide or veto it.”
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview about the possibility of counting the votes individually that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local election authority can count the ballots partially or completely.
For example, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted The results in the minutes do not coincide; the record on the counting and counting of votes is not in the record or it is not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or changes in the records.
In addition, the total counting of the full-filled ballots may take place if there is a difference between the presumed winner and the second-place who is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is an explicit request from the party-or coalition chairman who is the second of the aforementioned candidates.
The counting of votes may also be carried out in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that there is an explicit request from a representative of the party whose candidate has become second.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second place is almost 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral records have not yet been counted.
