The formation of the new Italian government
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce him to the new government to face the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce him to the new government to face the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the government formation.
It is assumed that he will present a cabinet composed by a majority of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of talks with political parties on government formation.
"I would like to reiterate my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former EU commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of a government, but his comments indicate that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well fixed,” he added.
Monti managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal.In the meantime, Italy is struggling with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must pass a tough austerity package demanded by European politicians in order to regain the lost confidence in Italy.
The pressure to rush on Monti was further intensified by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were charged with 7 percent interest for 10 years.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industry association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: “We said we would support this government with all our strength.”
We believe this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Montis’ chances of success have been greatly increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are aimed at delivering good results," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is essential, because so far many of its members have voiced opposition to a government made up mostly of technocrats, which Monti is currently forming.
Support from Parliament
Monti’s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to its efforts or delaying reforms could again cause a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also exerting pressure by pointing out that a Montis failure is a catastrophe.
Monti began on Monday with his debates with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
The round of session will be closed on Tuesday.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who initiated an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief rush towards the end of last week, when it became known that Berlusconi would resign, due to the uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister, the cost of Italian government bonds has reached critical limits again.
Saving Italy with a state debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout scheme.
Monti said his administration would have to last until the next election, which is expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms rather than prefer elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it should only consist of technicians, a reminder of their concerns over the procedure imposed by the pressure of the financial markets.
Political sources point out that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties complicate the inclusion of people from political life.
