Fujimori returns to hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be examined for muscle loss in his legs, his family doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who served 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, who has been operated four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas Hospital to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons.
He was operated on tongue cancer four times and lost 18 kilograms of weight. Additional diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Fujimori has been in custody at the Dirección Nacional de Operaciones Especiales de la Policía since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squadron of the Peruvian army, which was acting secretly during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will begin its visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón on Wednesday, which will be the culmination of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries," the office of the South American country announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón’s support in the incident with France, when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community.This statement was rejected by Uruguay and triggered a request from his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and industrialized countries. Since January this year, an agreement has been in place on the exchange of tax information to avoid double predisposition with the South American country.
In recent years, the government of Uruguay has sought to accelerate the specification of agreements for the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
At the business level, there has been a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which has contributed to an increased trade in goods between the two countries.
Super Mario 3D Land enters the third dimension
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to rescue Princess Peach from the claws of the evil Bowser, but so far never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he fights for the love of the girl in stereo technology.
The game, which comes to the shops around the world this month, has been tailored from the very beginning to the features of the portable console Nintende 3DS, which allows you to play three-dimensional without a special glasses.
“Mario is the character who has to tell how stereoscopy works without glasses,” said Omar Álvarez, the head of the Nintendo-specialized press in Spain, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez explained that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game to be developed for this console from the outset" because so far hit articles such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of Time 3D" have been adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman stressed that although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is a "accessible" video game that allows for a fast, fluid gameplay.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: The first part is "easy" to capture the less shitty users.
After that, the experts can turn a "second round" over the different levels of play, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
In addition, users can choose between an "aggressive D" in real time or one that only affects the depth of the action.
This trip of Super Mario into the three-dimensional world also means the character’s return to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo cries to the fans of the saga and repeats the recipe for success in recent editions: The crawling installor must overcome dangerous platforms to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news about the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies – and a “playable” Luigi.
Colom guarantees Portillo’s extradition to the United States
Guatemala President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he would accept the extradition of former governor Alfonso Portillo to be held accountable in the United States for the conspiracy to launder $70 million.
The trial ends with the U.S. request for Portillo’s extradition so that he can be brought to court there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and government, considering that a ruling court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that during his reign he did not interfere in court decisions and granted all extradition requests he was notified of.
With the exception of Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is extradited for murder and serious injury, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
The Coloms Act is a government act that takes place after all the judicial and constitutional instances for convicting the former state president (2000-2004) have been exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited if his legal situation in Guatemala is clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for undermining 120 million Quetzales in the Ministry of Defense during his reign. This trial preceded his extradition, but the minister objected and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organization was established to prevent the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of Trinijove’s life have brought important results: in this quarter-century, 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion have been helped to find a way out of their difficult situation.
More than a hundred jobs have been created for this group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, a record was drawn yesterday at an event in the former Fabra i Coats factory buildings, which attended more than 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the district of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with low education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginalization.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous leaders of institutions and institutions who have worked with the association over the past 25 years.
The participation of political representatives from different directions in election campaign times demonstrated the impartiality of the work done by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol attended the celebrations the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and at the time left-green city council Ricard Goma.
The great hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was founded in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far "is a good foundation."
For the president of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in trouble.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house where giant parties were held was cleared
The homeowners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes Street No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve occupants left the building yesterday afternoon without resistance.
Everything suggests that the nightmares of the neighbors of House No. 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people volunteered yesterday at noon to leave the building they held illegally occupied and where they had organized huge parties that had driven the neighborhood to despair.
After the clearance, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the home administrator confirmed.
The occupants, who occupied 11 of the building's 13 apartments - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply with them.
In the three lower floors, huge parties were celebrated, lasting up to two days, pushing tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a disco, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the start of the occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the house occupants were making their unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while those in the discotheque cost 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the recreational room had been indicated by the neighbors for disruption of retirement, while, according to her statement, the noise did not come from the visitors to the disco, but from the occupants of the house and in particular from the guests of the parties organized there, and which, according to the angry neighbors, have become more and more in recent weeks.
The manager of the discotheque explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the past nine months.
The Guardia Urbana also confirmed that it has received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular) in the city council of Barcelona, Alberto Fernández Díaz, last week called for the building to be cleaned immediately and the problems of civil coexistence and the downturn of the district to be addressed.
He explained that before the summer only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the house occupants had penetrated all floors of the building and almost all apartments.
In this sense, he added that “it is necessary to put an end to impunity and take action against the antisocial acts in the building.”
Yesterday, another building in the district of Nou Barris was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 15:30, police approached Montral Street No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people trying to break into the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountain?
The architects, apart from the disputes over the fees, agree with the tender.
The city bidding for the 16 gates reopens the debate about the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-disappeared Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its blasphemy about the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in the city of Barcelona.
It was even compared in numbers to New York’s Central Park.
With the collapse of the CMB in 1987, the park became in the eyes of many again the upper border of Barcelona, as the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in the north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park plays with this idea.
The model was no longer the Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild pigs in the role of the yogis.
This was the point when the city issued a huge tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for additional access doors to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either it is so, or someone is planning to set goals on the ground.
The question arises: Collserola, park or mountain?
Not only from an organisational point of view, but also in terms of a reflection on the city, the tender is the subject of conversation in the mouths of all architects from Barcelona.
It’s almost a recurring topic that two members of this old-fashioned caste who meet in the elevator can resort to.
And this fact provides the fabric for one of the rare coincidences between what three architects from Barcelona think about and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Roldán, it is "necessary" to speak over the "front on the mountains" after the attack on the coast, as far as Ildefons Cerda's discourse on the green apples has not been delivered.
“One should assume that Barcelona’s biggest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is very accessible.
Collserola is more complex," judges the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" holds a "lexical trap" in itself: one should not imagine it "as accesses to a park, but as a limitation of areas where action must be carried out."
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona with urban experience, sees the proposal as a "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers".
Dangers arising from "the uncertainty that the design of a public space brings with it today" according to the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the area of the forum.
The first fear is your own limitation to what can be built.
“To limit something always means to set the next step,” that is, to go beyond it.
"We need to think about new urban planning tools, because the current [relating to the General Metropolitano (PGM) plan] can lead to a real catastrophe."
Modol, who holds closer to the issue, simplifies the view that the side of Collserola, which goes toward Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that does not go toward Barcelona", for purely topographic reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study from the patronage of de Collserola that should not "take on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving its panel the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
Furthermore, he notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the guidebook that allows the architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his “doubts” as to whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams set up (“just the right thing,” he says) “We architects should only be a tool.”
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the headline of this article is complex because the tender terms lack a global view of Collserola: "There have been 16 cross-section competitions," he says, "on the mountain-sea axis.
This has at least in his case led to his participation in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should necessarily guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped throughout its length to create a smooth transition between the city and green areas.
