MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence" to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI clinic, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
Interested people can come to the IMSS sports venues in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are conducted every Saturday from 8 p.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuauhtémoc sporting field (in the west of the state of Mexico) and has continued since 8 October at the Nezahualcóyolt sporting field (in the east of the state of Mexico).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study is continued at the Independencia sports court (in the south of the capital district) and completed at the Morelos court (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and role of genetics associated with the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On World Diabetes Day, he stated that the goal is that three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 should fill out nutritional questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He further noted that on the aforementioned Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors were determined (attempting to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out on the occasion of healthcare professionals’ concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
“Health surveys from 1999 and 2006 found that in just six years the proportion of obese boys has increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the Mexican population differs from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican is 65 percent Indian-American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, reflecting in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained, the genetics of obesity is expressed in the inability to burn the excess of energy (calories) taken from us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants would be a comprehensive examination of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even examine the presence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and on the inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of pre-stage metabolic disorders and diabetes.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors.The doctors explain all measurement results to the parents and suggest them lifestyle changes that are appropriate to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there would be three basic factors responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV, and using means of transport, instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. an increased consumption of sugary beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) along with a high fat and protein intake, as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from the UNAM prevents bump holes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM, has developed asphalt modified with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations.
Being attentive to the signs coming from the road cover, it would not be necessary to repair 200,000 bump holes if the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning and assuring that if the layout and maintenance of the asphalt coating is done properly, the number of bump holes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Block holes from a technical point of view" he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce an asphalt-like mixture, but that has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera argued that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road cover and thus avoid the appearance of bump holes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes.
The elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very tenuous and at 50°C it is almost firm, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"That means that the resistance of the asphalt on the streets is not uniform, but changes in a day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible street coating consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wearable layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good power distribution on the road.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," the chemical engineer said.
"Over the wear layer," he concluded, "is laid a last layer, the so-called carrier layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
Because these layers are in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
In addition to receiving and distributing the most forces from this road coating, the support layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material it consists of must beined.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates into the layer and it is only difficult to come out again.This causes the softening of all layers of the road cover and, as a result, the appearance of bump holes.
When a hole occurs,” he said, “the ceiling layer is first worn off and the wear layer is only damaged afterwards.But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that needs to beined at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs.”
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause of shock holes.Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road coating must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is observed to avoid frequent shock holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the hole can be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
