Entry of a “Golden Budget Rule” into the Constitution
Austria’s ruling government, a large social-democratic/Christian-democratic coalition, decided on Tuesday to incorporate a “golden budget rule” into the constitution to reduce public deficits and also to avoid possible degradation by rating agencies in Austria’s top bonity (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who personally announced this decision of the outcome of the Council of Ministers, although the public debt of Austria is at 74.6%, that is, far above the criterion of 60%, set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt level of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
