The Energy Policy:
Facts win over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be addressed on the basis of short-term considerations or on the basis of emotions, this is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to hold an election meeting to reflect on this topic and the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be fruitful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, the shortage of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity consistently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to tackle climate irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which subjects its decision to the need to find a substitutable source, nor in Switzerland, which just intends to build only nuclear power plants of the last generation.
However, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, in turn, has decided to add another unit to its park after Fukushima by re-entrying the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model focused on renewable energy is occasionally set as a model, however, the reality contradicts the discourse.
The elections in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, increased by the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will become noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives rise to reflection.
Denmark, on the one hand, is the European leader in wind energy, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill compared to our French households.
As the energy price plays a key role in the globalized economy, as well as the stability of the industry nationwide, the French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a sharp rise in energy prices, making noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are not willing to pay as much as they demonstrate resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has enabled us to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a multitude of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France decides to withdraw from nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual €6 billion in investment goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would hire an EPR designed to operate for sixty years if the decline of its producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, one must admit that there is no miracle tool for generating electricity, just as there is no devil’s work.
The low-carbon solutions for the use of nuclear and renewable energy developed by the company Areva testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of security is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks at existing plants such as the Flamanville building.
Those working teams that have made themselves a name because of their professionalism are just obsessed with the idea of security.
In the past 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major disruptions.
Only one, in Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; so it went without consequences for people and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was sparked by reactor construction and endless human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, causing the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as a cooperation between the security authorities of the French and German operators and engineers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a draft that enables it to be resilient to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electricians to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF, letting them free track to take on leadership in the inevitable nuclear development.
It is inevitable and legitimate to look for the best energy package for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party manipulations dominate a debate that equally determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
