Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It will supply gas to the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glory and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, on Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at a buffet.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically turned the steering wheel of the valve that carries Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will be delivered annually through a first pipeline of 1.224 km that connects the region of St. Petersburg with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania to Western Europe.
A second pipeline, which will allow a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of the total French consumption - is expected to be completed at the end of 2012.
The possibility of building a third line on the same route has already been announced.
For Gazprom, the timely and accurate completion of this enormous construction is a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable a direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any crossroads by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on land routes.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a bit of their power: it is now becoming harder for them to put pressure on Russia by threatening to block access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, the most engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the Nord Stream pipeline to a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically very sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, at the expense of a depreciation of European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has managed to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have high gas consumption and their gas reserves are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing to the extent to which the large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smile of the Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas pipeline.
The construction of this gas transmission pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel with concrete coating, which is designed to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, in approximately 200 m depth.
During its construction, mining fields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
"About a hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed for caution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Furthermore, increased measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The cable is a long metal string, weighing as much as 242 Eiffel towers, which is interrupted over the entire length by nothing: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refrained from it because the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company settle permanently at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we will close the gas door in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission can thus escape into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, as the welding seams were estimated to have a durability of one leak per 100,000 years.
State surveillance of gas transmission is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a sea ship, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas transmission pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures a meter in diameter, is inserted into the inside of the pipeline and moves through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device at its arrival provides the most accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The gas transmission pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance point and 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E.ON and BASF are affiliated here (15,5% respectively), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French company group GDF Suez (9% respectively).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
Its headquarters is in Switzerland, where taxation is inexpensive.
Gazprom has subsequently leased the entire capacity of its gas transportation to this company, under a 20-year renewable contract.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of how large the real amount of gas that is transported falls out,” Jens Müller said.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total labor costs are expected to be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are sure to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline comes to light on a sandy, wooded coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meters high valves form the gas exit gates.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other indicators of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, at candlestick hours spent with writing.
Moleskine’s notebook is easily recognisable, with its black, rectangular bandage, its rubber ribbon, its egg-shell-colored sides, as aged over time.
The Moleskine notebook, as it is known today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, headquartered in Milan, decided at the time to bring a distinguished design notebook to the market.
Maria Sebregondi, then a specialist consultant for the company, is in charge of launching the new product on the market.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a wool coating that is used, for example, for coating pads.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object, which until the 20th century was considered an icon of avant-garde artists,” explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes in.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first few years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a fantasy picture of the buyers, as the notebook enthusiastically enthusiasticates business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now employs more than 100 people and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebook books in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centers and is keen to assert its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of time and its new writing need, which persists despite the rise of emails," explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called “Detour” in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebook books.
In August, the company also launched a bandage with leopard patterns at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural spirit of time and learned how to diversify its products: bags, schedule calendars, fillers, computer envelopes... The brand has the entire range of items.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, opening a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week of Work for Disabled People begins today.
Despite a purposeful public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities is always twice as high as the average: 19% versus 9% unemployment rate of the total population.
and disappointing?
“No, so emphasizes Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which hosts the ‘Work Week for Disabled Persons’.
“The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable.”
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher.
“H, there is still a lot to do.”
However, it must be said that there are still numerous obstacles for disabled unemployed people to get a job.
It affects older people more often: 37% are older than 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them have no bachelor’s degree and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with a higher education degree.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% among people with disabilities versus 38% overall.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter work, and that are "the core of the problem," says Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes of mind, which, though certain, yet slowly evolve.
A study conducted in April by the IMS Entrepreneurs Association for La Cité magazine stated that the managers surveyed had “a weak level of knowledge about disabled people” that was “overrepresented” by “persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled.”
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees have a long way to go before reaching the target of 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a 1987 law.
These last figures, dated from 2008, refer to a rate of 2.6%.
"We are now around the 3%," said Pierre Blanc, general director of Agefiph, the organization tasked with collecting contributions from companies that disobeyed this law.
The evidence: The number of "tax-paying" establishments and the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011 decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which provides for tax increases, has put a lot of pressure on companies,” said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large corporate groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the facilities employ disabled workers between 20 and 49, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
